description.text:
I wanted to create a simple to print, detach and mount case/holder for the Raspberry Pi ZERO (W).

Load
Slice
Print
Enjoy

  1. It has only one part
  2. You don't need any screws
  3. You have detach helper (see pictures), use a small screwdriver or something similar
  4. Because of the "springs" in the middle, the case is flexible (that's why you can push the raspberry easy into it)
  5. The mounting holes have a distance of 70mm, so you can also mount it on a VESA 70 Monitor/TV

(Mind the notes in "Print settings"!)

Have fun

Printer:

RepRap NEO

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Z:0.1mm, Nozzle: 0.2mm

Infill:

20% Rectilinear

Notes:

In case its to narrow for your RaspiZero, try "Slic3r"-Settings:
"Advanced" -> "Other" -> "XY Size Compensation" = "-0.15mm" (this is for my 0.2mm Nozzle, the bigger the nozzle, the higher this setting should be; and note the MINUS in the value)

See the last picture in the gallery...

description.text:
The Zim Zeepro is a fun little printer, but the designers took a few shortcuts that can be annoying. One of those shortcuts is not doing a better job of securing the 6 mm shafts that the carriage rides on. Over time, they can push themselves through the support blocks and jam the mechanism. (I didn't take the mechanism apart, but I think they are just held in by prayers and good wishes.)

I printed a couple of bushings for each shaft, held together by M2x8 screws and nuts (although in my particular print, the holes threaded to the screws just fine and I didn't need the nuts at all).

Just install 1 bushing at each end of each rod to prevent it from sliding and you're good to go.

description.text: My Logan turning lathe's threading reversing gears shattered while attempting to make a worm drive with fast lead threads (5 1/2 threads per inch). The carriage hit the tailstock when I mistakenly started the lathe in reverse. New gears are very expensive and can cause other gears throughout the threading transmission to fail...so I decided to make a set of 30 tooth reversing gears from Taulman 910 alloy nylon to replace the cast iron originals. The nylon gears have several advantages. First they offer an inexpensive replacement. Second they run much quieter and most importantly they prevent any of the other gears from being damaged in the event of a crash of the carriage. (I have already tested this....twice) the only damage is to the nylon gears which are easy and inexpensive to replace. I now keep two replacements on hand at all times.

title: Printable Hinge Easel
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Printable Hinged Easel is really a multipurpose Thing. You can use this to display photos, cards, Mobile Phone/iPads/Tablets on tables.

The best thing is that, you don't need to print this thing as separate parts. This design is compatible to be printed in one go.

Curious, George? The tolerance is 250 microns inside the hinge.

One nifty idea is to use your old iPhone or and iPad as an digital photo frame. How cool would that be?!

Please note: The design may need some subtle changes if you choose to re-scale it in your 3D-slicer or some other CAD compatible program. The hinge is designed to work effortlessly with the set parameters. Re-scaling will not render it obsolete but the hinge might be loose or tight depending on the scaling factor.
Also, the product photos show a slightly scaled down version of the original model. The original model will have a smoother rotation.

Thank you!

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Infill:

33%

Notes:

User amcolley's question (see comments) compelled me to add this section to the Thing's page. The hinge is a live joint and needs to work as seamlessly as possible. Thus you need to align the easel upright while slicing and then printing. This will make your work as an end-user and the printer's job as a machine much more easier!
Hope this helps.

comments.text:
I know this is a difficult print to complete but I would suggest you to dial in your printer extremely well before starting off. Place it upright i.e. the same way you can see it in Thingiview and print with supports and turn on the layer cooling fan (PLA only) around the layer when you saw the supports break loose. I would also suggest you to go slow with printing this one. Don't exceed 40-45 mm/sec speeds.
Hope it works out! :)

comments.text: Can I print this laying down, or does it need to print upright?
comments.author: amcolley

comments.text:
Hi! Thanks for checking this out. You could print laying down as well but I would suggest printing upright. The hinge has no touching components when sliced either way but print wise, upright would be easier. Printing it laying down would probably make the hinge rod unplayable and make it too tight!
Hope this helps. :)

title: Tatara A8 Steel Frame - Anet A8 Swap it - V1.00

description.text:
This is a steel frame improved design for Anet A8 3D printer.

Version 1.1 code name Hayabusa is out, beginning January 2018, if you want to laser cut maybe you want newer version. -> https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2736479

(For A6 Version go here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2693658)

My self and Tommaso Collini (https://www.thingiverse.com/musta/about) we tried to implement easy solution to solve common issue we found on Anet A8 printer and most of cartesian printers. We believe Tatara frame is the best steel frame you can build.
In our design all parts are inter locked that ensure great stiffness and perfect geometry on all 3 dimensions.
What is special in our design:

  1. XY frame to make all build more rigid, this is a major improvement against all others Cartesian Steel frame that let you push printing speed to 150-180mm/sec, 20-25mm/sec2 jerk 1200 mm/sec2 print acceleration with good quality
  2. We add the option to add 6 LEVEL FOOT to level the printer
  3. Nyloc/Lock nuts compatible by design
  4. many small improvement that make the frame incredible rigid with virtual no resonance during printing.
  5. Damn heavy, more than 9Kg only for frame. Because we are not overseas seller's weight is not a problem but a feature:
    -lower center of gravity
    -weight leads to a higher inertia and therefore less high-frequency vibration

Why Steel??
Steel is the material that gives the best ratio stiffness (young's modulus) vs cost/volume.
To achieve same stiffness with other materials you need to use, at least, a sheet 3 time thicker.

To be manufactured of carbon steel (requires painting) or stainless steel.
We strongly suggest the use of a material with a minimum Young Modulus of 196 GPa ( double check it before you get your frame cut).

Is designed for 3mm thickness (clearance is 3.2mm so maybe you can also use 1/8"-> 3.175mm but we did not try)

people who sell Tatara frame on internet don't give any % to the designers (us) then if you enjoy the Tatara frame ( or if you make money with it)
can be kind to TIP

All measurement are the same as Anet A8 and you have to change only the frame and maybe the screws (depend what length of screw you get on your original Anet A8).
The design will be under CC attribution share alike license 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/) as well the DXF laser cut draw.
The draw is done from scratch, by your humble servant.

The first prototype of the Tatara - Anet A8 Steel Frame as been tested by Steve DellaRosa.
Grazie mille Steve!!!

Since then more than hundreds users swap to Tatara A8 steel and push their 3D printing quality and speed to unknow frontiers.

Many users also decide to build a 3D printer from scratch using Tarara A8 Steel Frame.

This is to consider final version, if you decide to laser cut is at your own risk we don't give any guaranties.
ATTENTION: Maybe your laser cut service need to do the nesting and bridging for optimization.

We recommend laser cut service who can provide h7 tolerance cut, watch out some laser cut service do very very low grade cut.

You have 2 version of files: only essential pieces (are excluded: screen part, fix Y belt holder, Z end-stop holder) and standard version with all pieces.

KNOW ISSUE:
with stock Mother Board and stock firmware Y 0 is 5mm inside the heated bed,
refer here to correct the problem:
https://research.paolorudelli.com/2017/11/10/tatara-steel-frame-y-end-stop-issue-software-solution/?lang=en

Control board holes are moved slightly backwards for easyer operation, that means some boxes that use both holes from board and powersupply don't fit.

3D printed (needed or not) parts can be found (on my buddy account) here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2358104

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2730724

You can find the sheet with detailed screws numbering <-> part-list, here https://issuu.com/tatarasteelframe/docs/tatara_steel_a8_v100_-_parts_list
Or download the PDF file with the screws and nuts list.

ChangeLog:
V100b: final version before move to version 1.10, just clean up .DWG files
V100: small mod on X/Y Frame for cable pass through,
RC2 v04: mod Y front and back frame

### REMEMBER TO "Electrical Grounding" the steel frame !!!!!! ###

About the name: Tatara is the name of the forge where the steel for japanese sword is melted.

We design the Tatara frame from scratch, we start with a blank sheet and open mind trying to solve engineering problems that 3D printing presents to every designer,
we get inspired by all the errors and the work done by the community of 3D printing on the last years. Licensing our projects under CC licence share alike 4.0 is a way to give back to the community.

Bed support design on V1.00 take inspiration from P3Steel: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:157303
And from Prusa i3 improved for laser cut:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39889

comments.text: If you knew it was crap, you don't qualify as a worshipper ! As I wrote, play with it and if you are serious about 3D printing, go for a better design. What a joke !

comments.text: Acrylic isn't a bad material if you use it right - I'll take the Geetech Pro's flat-front acrylic frame any day over my A8's frame, which has no horizontal bracing of the top whatsoever. comments.text:
If all the people who bought a cheap 3d printer would have the money to get a higher grade one, we would not be here discussing.
For most, if not all, printers such as the Anet are an affordable entrance in the 3d printing world that can be nevertheless satisfying and doable little by little. Enhancing your own printer is part of the fun and a direct swap is at range for everybody and gives a definite plus over the stock one for a fair amount (if you find an honest cutting service).

title: Filament Spool Holder Stand 1515 Open Beam

description.text:
I had some 1515 open beams left from a printer build and I needed a new Filament Spool Holder. So I came up with this.
Depending on how long your open beams are you can change the high, but you need one open beam with a minimum length of 120mm (this is for the horizontal open beam, 120mm just!!! fits on the edges of the bracket). For sure you also could print some kind of 1515 open beam.

Spools with a maximum width of 112mm will fit.
Made a holder for Taulman Spools

It stands really good and the Spool does´t wobble around.

Printer:

Kossel XL

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

12%

Notes:

The base is 150mm x 150mm.
With good cooling settings you don´t need Support.
I printed in Hatchbox ABS, 235°C on Nozzle, 75°C heated bed, 45mm/s speed, 0.2mm layer, 12% Infill 3 outer lines with Raft and Support. Using 3DLac and Simplify3D.
The base fits the beams really tight, you can print (especially with ABS) a bit bigger, 0.2-0.3% would be enough. If you have some play with the beams you can use some M3x8mm screws and nuts to fasten the beams to the base and bracket.
You also can use PLA or PETG, but non too flexible Material because this should be stable ;-).

Turn the Bracket around so that the slot for the horizontal open beam is on top.
No need to do anything. If you use Raft/Support, for sure you need to clean this.

Fusion 360

I used Fusion 360 to design this. With Fusion 360 it is really easy to create such an object like this, especially the rounded shapes.

description.text:
I wanted to level my Printed of my Printmate3D with a BLTouch. For this I needed a mount direct to the Extruder head. This fits good to my Printmate, depending on what kind´d of Heartbreak you use (longer or shorter) you you can scale this in the z-axis. Sadly you really need to try this out, you don´t have much space to get the BLTouch working correctly.
You need to drill two holes into the wooden clamp for the Hotend, but this is no problem. All holes are for 3mm screws.
If you have any questions don´t hesitate to ask.

Here is a Video of the working BLTouch:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hKjThycnXYM

Yes

Supports are necessary, but you can try without if your bridging settings are really good.

I printed with Prima Select PLA white, 200°C on Nozzle, 45°C heated bed, 35mm/s, 0.2mm layer, 100% infill with Support using 3dLac and Simplify3D.
It is an easy part to print and works really well.
Clean the part after printing and be sure that the surfaces where the BLTouch is mounted and where this mount is screwed to the wooden part are clean and flat.
I used Fusion 360.

remixed_from.author: Sigismond0
remixed_from.title: Printrbot Metal Open Cable Chain Kit

title: Y axis cable chain mount for Wanhao Di3 / Monoprice Maker Select v2.1
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After installing a rear mount extruder fan shroud, I noticed it caught the heated bed cable quite often, thus I need to install a cable chain, but most of the cable chain mount were either clip on or bolt right onto the heated bed. My concern is the heated bed mount can easily melt if I crank up the temperature for printing ABS. Start brain storming whether if it is possible to create one without touching the heated bed.

This particular bed mount do mount onto the Y-axis plate instead of the heated bed, making use of the square cut hole on the plate. You insert it into the square hole and it clip to it and also latch onto the edge of the plate (see picture). If the square cut hole doesn't exist on your Maker Select v2.1 Y-axis plate, then this mount isn't for you.

Make use of Sigismond0's cable chain : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1060522 and remix it to make my Y-axis mount end. I specifically use the LINK-45-out.stl, LINK-90-out.stl and LINK-90-in.stl from Sigismond0's design. The cable chain has a slightly smaller bending radius to what I have noticed, wider than the default 7x7mm configuration. much loose than other build that I have tried and it can assemble the chain without desoldering the wire ends make it my choice. I didn't modify anything of the cable chain itself, so you can refer back to Sigismond0's design to get the STL.

Since the heated mount was just clip on to the Y-axis plate, no screws, no glue, to prevent it from popping off the plate, I played with the different chain link (see picture). Sigismond0's chain link have 45degree (which allow chain to bend both ways), and 90degree (only bend one way), so I play with that to force the cable to push downwards onto the plate when the Y axis move front and back. So far it holds and no popping out at all. and hasn't melt yet ;)

UPDATE Dec 30/2017 :
Made a horizontal version https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2737592

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select v2.1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Frame mount : Easy to print, no special instruction.
Heated bed mount : Need to print upside down (square insert facing up) with heavy use of support.
With Cura support configration-
Support type = Touching buildplate
Structure type = Lines
Overhang angle for support (deg) = 60
Fill amount (%) = 15
Distance X/Y (mm) = 0.7
Distance Z (mm) = 0.15

Frame mount : Remove the existing M3 screws for the Y motor mount and mount the frame mount with M3x10mm screws (original one was too short)

Heated bed mount : Remove heated bed and place it asside, insert the square into the square cut on your Y-axis plate and clip it to the edge of the plate, it should just snap in. Mount heated bed.

Assemble the chains off Sigismond0's cable chain (link above)

title: Equalises the pressure in the middle ear. Earpain / Freediving

description.text:
Ear pain.

You put a balloon over the flat side which your child blows up through their nose. The act of blowing up the balloon helps to open up the Eustachian tube, making it easier for fluid to drain from the middle ear. The balloon equalises the pressure to relieve the symptoms in the middle ear.
This also helps for people who experience ear pain during plane flights.

Freediving.

With this you can improve your ''mouthfill'' equalizing technique.

description.text:
This is an simple under shelf storage mount for CO2 bottles.

This design uses 8mm rods for stability. I used 8mm aluminum rods (hollow) that I cut to a length of 27cm.

Scale the model if you use material that is known to shrink (I used ABS and printed at ≥ 101%). If your printer prints fairly accurate you should be fine or just need a few turns with a drill bit. Rod mounts are designed with 8.1mm diameter which worked fine for me.

I would recommend against PLA.

title: Jumbo Bin for Hornady Lock and Load Progressive Reloading Press

description.text:
This is my Jumbo-sized catch bin for the Hornady Lock-and-Load Progressive press. It holds... well, quite a lot of fresh new ammo, compared to the stock Akro-Bin that comes with the press. The photos show 200 rounds of .40SW, and there's clearly room for 200 more, though I suspect the whole structure (including the sheetmetal beam supplied with the press) might be under a bit too much stress with a truly full load. I don't know. I haven't tried it because I tend to start packing the ammo into MTM boxes around 300 rounds. There's also a photo of the standard Akro-Bin being easily swallowed by the Jumbo-3D-Printed version, like an Indonesian python swallows a local villager.

The two parts are held together by 9 sheetmetal screws, size #4x3/8. Though I suspect you could barrrrely get away with 1/4" screws I don't think I'd recommend it, and the design is long enough to accept 1/2" screws too. I just happen to have tons of #4x3/8" around for other projects, and #4 sheetmetal screws (pan-head, philips drive, stainless if you're OCD) are readily available at your friendly neighborhood hardware store, or earth-swallowing home improvement big box for just a couple bucks. Remember, you need 9 of them. #4. 3/8" or 1/2" (which might be a little bit stronger, but not necessary, like I said, mine has 3/8" screws). Folks NOT using silly imperial-measurement hardware, who prefer to call .308 Winchester by "7.62x51 NATO" or... whatever, well, sorry I don't know which "M2" or some-such metric screw you should use, and anyway it might blow up your gun, and I am certainly NOT liable if that happens to you. I'm sure there's a conversion table online somewhere.

This model takes MANY HOURS to print. So... if your printer is quite idle, hey go for it! You can probably print both pieces at once by nesting them, though I'm guessing that will take upwards of 12 or 13 hours, unless you can optimize the heck out of your settings. In which case, please share them in the comments.

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

MakerGear M2

No

No

20% as usual

Notes:

I highly recommend PLA "Pro" or Plus, or however your favorite brand likes to call the latest "improved" recipe for slightly tougher PLA. I like eSun, but I'm sure others will be fine too.

Take care not to over-tighten the screws. If you hear cracking noises, STOP!!! Snug is plenty. The plastic is very grippy and these screws won't just wiggle out over time - they're also tapping the plastic while you drive them.

I've been trying to print them in ABS and the top cap comes out perfect every time, but the bottom cap starts out looking good and always messes up at the threading, I even tried printing it at the lowest speeds to see if that helps with the threads. Maybe ABS can't do threading well?
comments.author: leftshoe

comments.text: I had the same problem when I printed only one set. The printer alternates between the two parts until it finishes the top, then all it has left to print is the rest of the bottom. as it does this layer by layer there is not enough time for the previous layer to cool this tends to make a melted blob at the top of the threads. The solution to this problem is to print two or more sets per print. This way when just the bottoms are left, the head still has other parts to alternate between, allowing enough time for each layer to cool.
comments.author: leftshoe

comments.text: i've had success with ABS and PETG. i've not tried PLA yet, but i guess with the fan running at max it would work well for me!

comments.author: Rexipus

comments.text:
I have seen your new version and I like it.
Unfortunately, the print time is very long, otherwise I re-do a new version.
As regards the holes for the cabling, I too thought that the top holes were too small and also they are not in an optimal position.
For this reason, I did a cover for left side fan, this cap has three holes, please look at the attached file; i think that just one fan, in direction of the stepper driver, is enough.
I preferred to do so to avoid a new printout.
for what concern the air flow, I don't think there will be temperature problems, first of all because I intend to leave the box open, without cover, I like to easily see the contents of the box and then because I suppose that the stepper drivers don't reach a too high temperature, they are well designed and with a good dissipation due the internal layer of the PCB.
I come from an old-fashioned engineering culture, which says more or less that "what is not there can not be broken"
I do not like to delegate the safety of a system at objects that can be accidentally broken, in our case, delegate a safety of a board to a cooling fan is, in my opinion, a risk.
if the stepper driver will be too hot, there is enough space to paste a heatsink above the driver case, but I think that this will be not necessary.
Any cabling that i do, was put inside a nylon sheath.
in any case, thank you for your great job.
comments.author: Rexipus

description.text:
This is a remix of the panoramic head by BlacklightShaman. It is a very nice design - I especially like the quick release mount. I added a few mods to make it easier to use with my setup. These are as follows:

Horizontal arm:

  • added alignment marks around the pivot point at 30 degree intervals
  • made a cavity in the bolt area to accept/capture a nut for a 1/4" dia. x 20 bolt
  • made a hole under the bubble level cavity so you can use a thin rod or drill bit to push the bubble level back out if you want to remove it.

Vertical arm:

  • added alignment marks around the pivot point at 90 degrees

Transversal arm:

  • added alignment marks around the pivot point at 30 degrees
  • lengthened the quickmount plate bolt channel to allow the plate to slide further back
  • added a groove past the end of the channel to allow for the quickmount cam bolt protrusion
  • added a small hole past the M5 nut pocket in the pivot area to allow use of a small rod or drill bit to remove the nut from the pocket

Quickmount socket:

  • moved the M5 nut pocket to the center of the socket.

Quickmount plate:

  • thickened the plate and made the bolt cavity deeper so that the head of a 1/4" dia. x 20 bolt does not interfere with the socket.

Knobs:

  • changed the heights of the knobs so you only need a few types of bolt lengths.

Also, I enlarged the nut cavities in the components to make it easier to install the nuts.

Hardware Required and General Notes

To assemble this remix you will need the following hardware:

  1. M5 x 36mm bolts (2x)
  2. M5 x 45mm bolt (1x)
  3. M5 nuts (6x)
  4. M3 x 16mm bolts (1x)
  5. M3 nuts (2x)

Item 1 is for the horizontal to vertical arm connection, and the quickmount socket to transversal arm connection
Item 2 is for the vertical arm to transversal arm connection
Item 4 is for the quickmount cam to socket connection

In addition you will need hardware to mount the head to the tripod and the camera to the plate. I used 1/4" dia. x 20 x 1/2"L bolts and nuts for my setup.

Notes:

A. The quickmount socket knob will interfere with the vertical arm if you want to take upward-facing shots. In this case you can eliminate the knob and just use an M5x16mm bolt instead, but you will lose the ability to adjust the position of the socket on the transversal arm without using tools. If you use the same camera/lens all the time on the head this won't be a problem since you won't need to adjust this anyway once you have it set.

B. You can eliminate the horizontal arm knob and just use a bolt instead (similar to A.) if you use the same camera all the time, since you won't have to adjust this once you have it set. This is true even if you change lenses since the camera base to lens centerline distance does not change.

C. For the quickmount cam, make sure the M3 bolt head is on the cam side of the mount. This is so that the bolt protrusion under the socket will be able to pass through the channel in the transversal arm.

description.text:
I printed the cable chain by papinist and soon found out that the chain can come above the bed when your bed is moving in far top the inside. You can damage your nozzle when it moves over the chain in that position. To keep the chain below the bed I created a little arm based on the bed spring protectors from AndrewUsov.

I printed in PLA - 190 nozzle - 40 bed - 80% - 0.2mm.

Check https://youtu.be/ceR3x_IF9tU

comments.text: Just use a scrap of 400 grit sandpaper on your links before assembly and they will stay down with gravity.
comments.author: mudnuri

comments.text: You did not read the other comments. There is no friction between the chain parts. Without the copper cables the chain works like a charm. Just like those toy snakes. The issue is the stiffness of the copper cables you use inside the chain. So no need to use sandpaper at all. Just use flexible copper cables and even then you might see the chain come up.
comments.author: mudnuri

comments.text: I found a chain that only bends one way and 45 deg per link. Thanks for making me think about it though. Are you using a cold bed with that?

comments.text: I used 14 of them. I have the same problem with the chains. But I have a question. Doesn't this solution push the bed upwards? I don't know how much force is applied.
comments.author: Salami

comments.text: There is no force at all. At least a small amount of force. The problem is the electric cables inside the chain. The more flexible the copper cables are the less it will rise. If you completely remove the copper cables the chain will not rise at all. The protector will asure that the chain keeps below the bed.

title: Universal Outernet Case for the DIY Kit (Any elevation angle)

description.text:
This is a 3D printable case for the Outernet DIY kit. It can be used for any satellite elevation angle. The Case is 15,3cm (6") tall, 13.6cm (5.35") wide and 4.4cm (1.73) thick.

The SDRx and CHIP mini pc can be screwed to the main part of the Case. They will be connected to each other over a short usb cable (micro usb to Type A / charging cable).The Patch Antenna just slides into the case. The Stand is screwed into the two m3 nuts that are placed in the main case. The elevation angle will be set trough tightening the scrwes after positioning the case in the right angle.

Discussion and any suggestions on the Outernet forum: Universal 3D printable case

You need the following additional parts:

  • two m3 screws and nuts
  • two micro usb cables (short ones will work)
  • micro usb extension (optional for a socket in the back, replaces one usb cable)
  • 30mm 5v fan (optional for cooling)
  • a sheet of plexiglass or acrylic (optional, 130x125mm 4mm thick or less)

Printer:

Zonestar D810

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

All parts are already oriented like they should be.

Take a look at the positioning in thingiview to check the orientation before printing to be on the save side.

Build instructions
  1. Insert the two m3 nuts into the main case and mount the stand with two m3 screws to the Main case
  2. Mount the SDRx and CHIP in the Main case with m3 screws
  3. Connect both of them with the USB cable and plugin the power cable to the CHIP
  4. Connect the Patch Antenna and slide it in
  5. Mount the fan in the Back Covor and install it on the case (optional)
  6. Use a 4mm thick plate of acryl to cover the Antenna (optional)

description.text:
Reliable knuckle duster

In stock it is made for 21.5 mm index finger in width, so you should scale it for your hand using the formula:
a-your index finger width (in mm)
(a+1.5)/23 x 100%

for example I have 18 mm index finger:
(18+1.5)/23 x 100%=19.5/23 x 100%=0.847 x 100%=84.7%
Don't forget that all hands are different and if it suits bad, you can use file to adjust the size

description.text: Remix of the Draugr for printability.

READ BEFORE PRINTING!
The files are too big to upload to Thingiverse, I can compress them but it would lose too much detail. You can download the files in the link in the description. All files uploaded to Thingiverse are test files or first proof of concepts, not the final sole.

I Love sneakers! I'm on a quest to replicate the adidas Futurecraft 3D printed soles.
This is my first test.

http://www.3ders.org/articles/20151007-adidas-materialise-to-present-futurecraft-3d-printed-sneaker-the-future-of-running-shoes.html

The final sole consists out of two parts. I printed them in TPU with 5 perimeters and 50% Infill. Since the files are too big for thingiverse, you can download them on my onedrive.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/16ulRKOxNLgfNDbF7O2FLPhJ92gwGfW_0/view?usp=sharing
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1JDJN6YiIsIfAYg9O44YTjaAOtXEiKLV1/view?usp=sharing
I used contact glue (400ml) to glue the TPU to an ultraboost upper.

Good luck!

Use these tables to scale the sole to the right size of your foot. The original is size 45
http://www.tennis-warehouse.com/LC/shoesizing.html

Would love to see your results!

Printer:

Tronxy p802ma

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

50-100

Notes:

I printed the final result in TPU
I included 3 files to test out the flexibility of your materials, they all have different lattice thicknesses and lattice densities.

Solidworks and Meshmixer

I designed the sole in Solidworks using an Ultra Boost as reference.
Then I cut the sole in 3 parts and used Meshmixer to add the lattice structure to the middle and combine the top and bottom of the sole with the middle part.

Boost Material information

"Boost material" is the first expanded thermoplastic polyurethane (ETPU),
which BASF is marketing under the name Infinergy™.

For more info about boost material download the pdf on the BASF website. (link below)

https://www.basf.com/en/company/news-and-media/news-releases/2013/07/p-13-301.html

Printing each 1/2 sole took about 20h Removing support material was pretty difficult. I used a sharp scalpel for this. After cutting and pulling the original sole of the donor shoe. Had to make some repairs after cutting of the sole The original (fake) ultraboost and the soles ready for gluing I used the sole of the donor shoe to clamp down the out-sole to the printed sole while gluing. use clothes pegs if you don't have enough clamps I added a bag of sugar in the sole to apply even pressure everywhere on the sole.

http://k8200.vandegroepjes.nl

I wanted to create a Small Stellated Dodecahedron (small being part of the technical name, to distinguish from the Great Stellated Dodecahedron). There are lots of papercraft versions as well as 3D print versions, but I'm a big fan of laser cutting and I couldn't find any laser cut ones. I had two prior attempts which didn't work very well - but this one went together pretty easy with wood glue. I used 1/8" birch plywood. The joints are a little loose, so I'm going to try to make it fit together more snugly in my next run. I'll update if it works well!

The design file needs to be cut 3 times to get all the parts. The whole thing can be cut from a 12"x12" piece of material.

I used Wikipedia to look up geometry information about the Small Stellated Dodecahedron, and decided on a strategy using intersecting pentagrams. The trickiest part was getting the connecting pieces right (the intersection angle is 116.565 degrees) - the rest is just pentagons and triangles.

Designed in DraftSight, prepared in Inkscape, cut on a Full Spectrum 80W Laser Cutter at Make 717 in Lancaster, PA.

comments.text:
That's because the Air from Hot-end fan(front) and Air from Cooling fan(on side) was colliding inside X carriage cover and create so called Air curtain which blocks most off the air blowing in the printing part. Now air blows directly under tip off nozzle where it should be for PLA prints but now that affect ABS prints because ABS don't need any cooling(in most cases) Even if you turn off cooling fan completely OFF Hot-end fan will still blow at 100% rate on the hot end and most of that air will blow at the print.
That makes ABS material to cool down to fast and cause bad quality ABS prints on CR-10. This problem can be solved by installing small buck converter on the 12V fan and then lower the speed of main Hot-end fan to the point that barely blows but still enough cool down the Hot-end. That will make ABS prints rock solid and way better than before.
Same Technique can be used on main fan inside control box cause its way too loud and spins way to much unnecessary. There is automatic fan on power supply so there is no worries that lowering RPM of main control box fan will cause any problems.
Not to mention that Heat-Bed can't warm up to at least 90C to get proper ABS print but that problem is solved by installing insulation cotton sheet under heat-bed after that Heat-bed can reach 100C so you can avoid to use enclosure.

description.text: Our Printrbot Simple uses 1/4" Acme threaded rod for the Z axis, and came with a piece of vinyl tubing as a coupler to the motor shaft. Sadly, we lost that little piece of tubing, and this printed coupling is our answer to that problem.

The coupler and nut should print easily without support. Depending on the motor you have the fit on the shaft may be tight; you can either drill out the shaft hole slightly, or if you print the part in PLA heat it with a hairdryer so it will slip on. If you have a flatted shaft one screw will suffice to hold the coupler in place, the second spot is provided for round shaft motors. I found that the coupling gripped the Acme rod tightly all by itself, but the printed nut is available to lock things together if needed. I recommend finger tightening only. If you want to tweak the parts in OpenSCAD you'll need the Thread Library for the Acme screw threads: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8793

I wonder whether the end of your rod was messed up when it was cut to length at Printrbot. It's easy to ruin the last turn of the thread, or leave a partial turn that won't start into the nut properly. It's hard to describe what the end should look like, though you can look at a manufactured bolt for an example of how the thread should start. If it doesn't look like that I'd suggest cleaning it up with a file, or a grinder if you have one (but be careful holding the rod so you don't damage it in the process).

Parts Needed: 6pcs - M5x30mm Bolts
6pcs - M5 Nuts
Additional support for the top of Z axis threaded rods ACME screws.
These supports were designed to work with 0.25" ID, 0.625" OD bearings -- the ACME lead screws I used had the ends turned down to 0.25".

comments.text: this method look cool, but leaves your Z-axis over-constrained. Every lead screw has a certain amount of wobble and this will (ever so) slightly warp your frame and lead to a wobble in your workpiece.
comments.author: JelleBoomstra

comments.text: an ACME leadscrew has a much higher tolerance for straightness than a standard metric threaded rod. The threadform is also a "square" thread, which is lower friction and generally more accurate than a threaded rod. ACME screws are commonly used in CNC routers. In this application (ORDbot-type 3D printer) the frame is very rigid, and the biggest shortfall to the original design is the metric threaded rod. The Z axis is not over contrained, as this mount simply contrains the top of the screw to prevent whipping, which can quickly destroy a leadscrew.
comments.author: JelleBoomstra

print_settings.Notes:: First model printed with .25 mm nozzle @ 50um layer height over 9+ hours. I used the split gun model @ 50% Prusa supplied silver PLA 210C/55C 30mm/s. .05 layer height, .5 wall, .4 top & bottom. Cura supports @ 10% were easy to remove but left ugly horizontal overhangs. The hanger bay (also supported by supports) turned out well so I'm not sure what's going on there.

description.text:
A maximum battleship concept for Homeworld 2's Hiigaran battlecruiser. I'm new to modeling so this is more of a mashup than proper modeling as I still havn't been able to fix Jooxoe3i's model enough for it to be a solid and easily manipulable model.

This is designed to be printed at 119% scaling for a 1/5000 scale model. This also allows for some more detail on the missile pods and a comfortable 22cm long model. Printing on the side or vertically allows the model to retain detail even when scaled down significantly but would be a weaker print than when printing flat.

May 2017 update: printing @ 50% with a .25mm nozzle or smaller works too! You could probably go a bit smaller in easy 'cut model' mode or super small when guns are oriented vertically. Strength laying down is no problem.

I plan to add ballast of some sort (lead/steel/sand and glue?)when I print for a heftier experience.

Ideas: Print image scaled to paper (top @ 88%ish for 22cm model on 8.5x11 paper) to visualize model and gun sizes.
Drill/melt interference hole on model for turret nail to simply be inserted. Friction should keep them from falling out. If model is sliced, retention hot glue glob can be used on the inside as a stopper.
Insert magnet when printing, securing with glue, for neat stand mechanics or fridge model.

To Do: Model stand, turret mounting mechanism for turret rotation, Fix Eye of Horus symbol for printing, design articulated barrel turrets

title: Box Mod bottom feeder mechanical with square push button lock (v3b p&p;)

description.text:
This is an upgrade (push button) of this project: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2152729
In this upgrade i used a mechanical push button with square section with a very efficient lock system.

The idea was: no solder, all plug & play.
U need only sold a small copper/silver/brass to negative drip cap ring: all the rest is plug & play.

File explanation:
body_squared_push_button_dripcap_hole_10_mm: body with drip cap hole 10 mm (fat daddy)
body_squared_push_button_dripcap_hole_12_mm: body with drip cap hole 12 mm (mav)
bottle_spacer: the spacer for soft round bottle
fat_daddy_pin_locker: if u use fat daddy v5, u need this to block the pin contact
front_panel: the front panel
square_base: push button base
top_cap: push button top
locker: push button locker
locker_big: push button bigger locker (to use if locker is too small for your hands)

To complete u need:

  • a drip cap;
  • some magnets 3x1 mm;
  • a brass/silver/copper strip: i used these http://fave.co/2cri1DS
  • keystone 5209: http://fave.co/2lI0utx or http://fave.co/2bsgxvX
  • a bottle

If u need a photo-tutorial u can follow this one > http://www.esigblog.com/box-mod-bottom-feeder-mini-meccanica-foto-tutorial/

If u need extra push button assembly explanation u can take a look to the shots in this project: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2212825

Suggested print setting: 150 micron (0.15 mm) for body and panel, 100 micron (0.10 mm) for push button parts.

Italian Tutorial
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TO2UMWDgJ0A

Converts continuous rotary motion of pinion into reciprocating rotary motion of C Gear. Derived from the book "507 Mechanical Movements" Video at http://youtu.be/DzJzle83oas

Printed in ABS with .2mm layer height. Print one of each. Depending on your printer's calibration, you may or may not have to glue a few of the mating pieces together. If parts to stay pressed together, glue the square end of the "C Gear Shaft" into the "C Gear". Glue the smaller OD of the "Pinion Shaft" into the ID of the "Pinion". Slide the "Pinion" thru the slot in the "Frame" and glue the "Crank" on to the square drive.  
The "Pinion" has a unique up-and-down motion while turning the "C Gear", and the "C Gear" will reciprocate back and forth.  
Spin and enjoy!!

comments.text: First time I came across this type of gears and I liked it and tried printing it. Ran into the same problem as others are mentioning. description.text:
Hi,
Also if now GEEETech proposes the Acrylic Prusa I3 pro series, B for single extruder and C for dual extruder, with metallic idler, I’ve see lot of people that still download my old customization for Printed idler, so I’ve think good to “port” the new version of my customization also on old, printed idler!
Here the X Motor Idler component of my new customization, you can see from attached picture the contacts are now decoupled on bottom of this component, so you can easy install!

You can see in Schema all components you need, and all the cables are 90cm length to avoid any complexity during installation

In the schema images you can see how all this cable are connected.

PLEASE PAY ATTENTION: the decouple is NOT SO EASY to create!
You must be good with a soldering iron!!!

As usual in all my design I’ve split all in order to have an easy print of each, and also an easy mounting after print!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

1x 4 Position Header (Male)
1x 1x2 Pin Header (Male)
1x 1x6 90cm Flat cable

Male Pin Header is usually sold in 1x40 pin that you can easily separate, and of course for any of these components you need symmetrical connector for Arduino side!

These were printed out fast because I wanted to see the results, slower speeds and finer resolution would have cleaned them up much nicer. Grab your favorite SVG file and make your own Maker coin after watching Joel's (3D Printing Nerd's) Fusion 360 tutorial, best 30 minutes you'll spend quickly learning the basics of a awesome and powerful program!

Fusion 360

After Watching Joel's video tutorial on Fusion 360 I was easily able to design and make this, my own Maker coin. The software is free if your non commercial (ie Hobbyist), so why not give it a try.

title: Discovery / Discoeasy montage moteur Z par le haut

description.text:
Bonjour,
Pour ceux qui n'arrivent pas a trouver les moteur de l'axe Z pour la discovery et/ou la discoeasy, voici une solution permettant d'utiliser des moteurs de taille standard sur cet axe.
Le moteur se monte simplement sur les pièces du haut.
Pour ce montage, il faut :
2 pièce imprimé : 1 normale et une symétrique
2 moteurs
4 vis M316 et 4 vis M312 pour fixer le moteur
4 vis M316 et 4 écrous M3 pour serrer les barres du haut
4 vis M316 et 4 écrous M3 pour serrer les barres de Z

Il faut mettre les écrous des barres du haut en premier car le moteur les recouvre après.
Le reste est identique a l'origine.

Je met le step en téléchargement pour ceux qui voudrait le modifier.

But any screw that's course thread and about 50mm long and no wider then 3mm (shaft) should be good to go. Versions 1.0, 1.1, 2.0, and 2.1 were done in Sketch up, Version 2.2 was completely rebuilt in Solidworks 2013  
On a Side note I have printed this shift nob and it does work on my car well. I will be uploading photos shortly. When I can take some photo's in good daylight.

print_settings.Notes:: This is done on a Printrbot Simple Metal Pro

description.text:
This is a modification of a "Parking Assistant" I found on "Intructables.com".(https://www.instructables.com/id/Arduino-Parking-Assistant/)

His version is in a wooden case and he does a nice job explaining how to create the case.
My version is in a 3D printed case I designed using "FreeCad" (Thanks FreeCad!)

His version uses discrete leds.
My version uses a neopixel ring from adafruit (WS2812) (https://www.adafruit.com/product/1463)
I modified his Arduino code to use the WS2812 led ring.

His version uses an Arduino pro mini
My version uses a "Trinket" from adafruit (https://www.adafruit.com/products/1501)

We both use the HC-SR04 sonic sensor (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MA4O5G5/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)

We both use a push button to set the initial parking distance. These are similar to the one I used. (https://www.adafruit.com/products/1119)

title: Phone with wallet case car cup holder Nexus 5x

description.text:
This is a case I've made to hold my phone in the car without having to remove it from the wallet case. It goes into a cupholder, the phone just wedges in the top with the case folded behind. It is designed for a Nexus 5x with a Mercury Goospery wallet case, but may also work for other phones. The slot is 16mm x 90mm.

The whole screen is accessible on the nexus 5x.

There is a central hole for a usb c charger in the bottom and one at the side for headphones.

I have added a version without the holes in the cup part (will be slower to print).
I've also shared the tinkercad files
Original
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/c4AF7womnzr-n5xcupholderv7
Without holes
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/85GSbJhhQCa-n5xcupholderv7no-holes
The link below file is for a plug to hold my usbC cable in the mount so no fiddling to plug it in. Does need to be a tiny bit larger (I just glued it in) and may not fit other usb cables.
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/l1gdSaugaow-usb-c-widget

The cup part is 75mm diameter, this fits perfectly in the pop out cupholder on a Mitsubishi Delica D:5, but may be a bit large for some cupholders, it won't fit the centre console holes. The previous prototype was 70mm which was a bit loose, but fitted all the holders.

Printed OK for me with no support in PLA, I've included some fillets to avoid too much bridging, but forgot about the triangular holes near the top, still came out OK on my anet a8. I used 20% infill, suspect it doesn't matter much as everything is so thin.

My first attempt at building something for 3D printing, although this is the second prototype. Seems to work quite well, but no doubt can be improved.

comments.text:
Further to last comment, I had a quick play myself and think I have succeeded in removing the holes, I have uploaded a no holes stl file, but I have not tried printing it so can't guarantee I didn't mess something else up.
I have edited the description with the tinkercad links. Also threw in tinkercad link for the widget I made to hold the USB cable in place. Still needs a bit of tweaking as it is loose if not glued, and probably needs to be adapted to specific cables, as the positioning is fairly critical, but it works great for me.

description.text:
My first attempt at designing something that I could print and use myself.

The spare batteries for my camera always end up mowing around in the bottom of my camera bag so I decided I needed a box to keep the spares in so that when I needed a spare they would still be in the same place as I put them.

This box holds two batteries. My intention is to put the charged batteries in with the contacts facing the top and the used batteries in with the contacts at the bottom so that I know which are the good batteries at a glance.

The top can be a very snug fit but if you decide to clean the inside of the box lid or the outside of the box body don't take too much out or the lid will be loose.

title: Hictop Prusa i3 3DP-17 - S-360-24 power supply cover

description.text:
This is a cover for the s-360-24 power supply that has a space for a volt meter and an IEC switched socket.

I removed the switch at the control board side, it is far better switching the mains at <2A than switching the 24V side at 15A!

The supply is like this one:

  • https://www.lulzbot.com/store/parts/24vdc-15a-360w-power-supply

Google around for wiring. For the meter I connected the red and white together to +ve and the black to -ve. For the switch I took the L and N from the socket to the switch and the other side of the switch to the L and N connections on the supply with the earth being straight to the socket. You can see the wires for the neon in the switch attached to the terminals, if you connect this side to power supply the neon will be on when you switch it on rather than all the time.

Be aware that the IEC socket requires a 20mm fuse, I got some 3.15A slow blow 250V fuses from ebay.

The meter and switched IEC socket are available on eBay. Titles (use to search for similar):

  • Panel Mount Rocker Switch IEC320 C14 3 Pin Plug Power Socket AC250V 10A EW
  • DC 0-100V Blue LED Digital Voltmeter Voltage Gauge Panel Meter Car Motorcycle

Design on Onshape if you want to copy and modify it:

  • https://cad.onshape.com/documents/74f86c40fefcb4393c2a779b/w/a348509dcebd8d896dafe29a/e/69eb6ac4fd1731622e59530e

13/05/2017 - Update: V7 - Enlarged wire holes and added second, added recesses for clips of the meter and socket. Not tested.

description.text:
In 2015 I purchased a Geeetech i3 Pro B printer kit with 8mm Acrylic frame. Attempts to use this printer has always resulted in unpredictable outcomes, so I set out to improve it (see my other things for successful improvements).

This specific improvement attempt gets rid of the LM8UU linear bearings under the bed, which are part of the Y-axis movement, and replaces them with something that is quieter and which allows me to remove the bed easily (after detaching the Y-axis belt), when needed.

I do not yet know the longevity of this part (of which you need 4), but so far it is working very well for me.

Printer:

Geeetech i3 Pro B with 8mm Acrylic frame

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Print with a material which has low friction and slides easily on steel. I used Taulman PCTPE (which is a Nylon composite) for this, but Igus iglidur, or other material intended for bushings may be more appropriate.

comments.text: hows this working out for you after some time? How does the friction compare? I'm tired of LM8UU's scarring my rods...
comments.author: agaskins

comments.text: @agaskins, this has been working very well for me since I printed them from low-friciton Taulman PCTPE filament and added them to my printer. I have had very smooth and quiet motion with no unexpected surprises yet.

title: Up Mini Temperature Mod 12 position switch 40x40mm Clip lock Enclosure

description.text:
I designed this small enclosure for my UP Mini printer to house the 12 position rotary switch used to change the Extruder temperature.  The switch I used is Digikey EG1951-ND together with 1.8 ohm resistors to give drops in temp in 5 degree steps  
You will need to drill your own cable hole as there are too many diameters to compensate for
Print out and assemble.  I used 200 micron resolution and solid fill.   I painted the clips with some acetone before using to ensure the layers were welded together properly.

comments.text: Try this link Mordy. I used regular resistors rather than surface mount as they were easier to wire to the rotary switch.  Simple and effective mod

description.text: This object has been developed as part of the art project "Whisper Down The Lane", currently being developed by Bronwyn Holloway-Smith in conjunction with the exhibition The Obstinate Object: Contemporary New Zealand Sculpture at City Gallery Wellington, New Zealand (24 February â€“ 10 June 2012). During the exhibition digital 3D models will be made of selected works in The Obstinate Object in collaboration with designers Ant Pelosi and Nick Graham. The files for these models will be released for free download on Thingiverse under a Creative Commons BY-SA-NC License. Each physical work in this series is also available for purchase through a manufacture-on-demand system. The models are being produced in New Zealand using the Open Source RepRap 3D printer (with Vik Olliver). Order editions on the project webpage: http://bronwyn.co.nz/projects/whisper-down-the-lane The project will start with one work and will then gradually grow over the course of the exhibition as new works are completed and released. To receive notifications of new releases follow @hollowaysmith on Twitter, or join the mailing list at http://bronwyn.co.nz/contact/

This digital file is for the legs of the stool only. Once these are printed, to assemble the stool follow these steps:
  • slot the narrower piece inside the wider piece forming an "X" junction.
  • Join the two pieces by slotting a piece of silver wire or similar through the small holes provided and trimming as appropriate. For the base rail cut and insert a piece of filament.
  • The fabric seat material in the official edition has been made using specially created paintings on canvas by the artist Raewyn Martyn, however you are welcome to make your own paintings on fabric to fit.
  • Cut the fabric in to a rectangle measuring 80mm x 45mm
  • Turn in the long edges to form 5mm hems and stitch with a small straight sewing machine stitch.
  • Cut the corners on an angle to fit between the top junctions.
  • Hot glue the two short edges to each underside of the tops of the stool

title: Macro Light / Flash for Lumix FZ1000 or other cameras

description.text:
Using a typical smartphone light from ebay you can change it to a three level macro light.

Throug the ring of LEDs the object throws nearly no shadow and gives you the possibilty to use higher dazzle numbers with a higher depth of field.

Order a ring from ebay (like http://www.ebay.de/itm/122124151855?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT)

Cut the front to a ring (there is no electronic inside but pay attention for the connetion point of the cables)

Cut the back, so that the eletronic parts and the battery case remains and glue it onto this thing

Use an adapter thread fitting to your camera. The bigger circle was designed to be 82 mm. Glue it together

Have fun and success on your macro photographie!

description.text:
DotBot Click is an educational robot whereby you can create robots with Arduino UNO R3, and all kinds of Raspberry Pi including PiZero.
 This robotic platform allows the students not only to learn robot programming, but also to modify easily the chassis and create new custom parts.

All parts of this robot fits perfectly between them without using any screw.
 Since it is an open source platform the robot can be freely modified, copied, and shared across the Internet. In addition, it is extremely cheap, in fact the cost is determined almost exclusively by the DC Motors, electronics and sensors. It has been designed to attach other components such as servos, DC Motors, LEDs, push buttons, buzzer, and other sensors.

This work was created by two professors:

Michele Maffucci - IIS Galilei Ferrari - Torino - Italy Ludovico Russo - Researcher - Politecnico di Torino - Italy

Build Instructions:
The robot assembly is easy. More detailed instructions can be found on this link: http://www.maffucci.it

description.text:
Upgrade Parts to use the Spool Holder for tables like the IKEA Lack.

Print them in 0.3mm, they don´t need to be beautiful, just functional.
0.2mm works too.

Update:

Updated the design and added the remaining parts for this spool holder from the original file from foosel.

As glue i recomment power glue or epoxy.

You need to print the following parts x times:

Base: 1
Side: 2
Rolls: 2
Washers: 4
Rollend: 4 (8, if you wand to glue the outher ones on the rolls and have variable ones inside)

Printer:

Hephestos 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2-0.3

Infill:

25

Notes:

Supports only needed for the rolls, each touching only the printbed.

Assembly

1st Step: Install the Screws, washers, bearings and nuts on the sides.

2nd step: Glue one side on the base.
Try without glue first, if the pins don´t fit, sand them a little.
After that, use epoxy or powerglue with an accelerator to mount the side on the base.
Look that the bearings show inside the base before glueing!

3rd step: Add the Rolls, put the second side on it and glue this also on the base.

Please note that this is a fixed solution, you can´t remove the rolls after that anymore without destroying one side of the holders.

You can also try to work without any glue, but i don´t know how stable this is.
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/ek0LlRgNX0V

When printing the ball you put your micro-sd card in at around 70% finished (Pause and put it in). Start the print again and it seals it self and then your SD-card is gone in the ball and is now secure!
Read "READ ME.txt" for more instructions!

Includes ball without number and with number 1 to 3. It also includes 2 ball stands.

Read the "READ ME.txt"-file to see how it works :)

Includes 6 files:
Micro_SD_Ball_Without_Number.stl
Micro_SD_Ball_Number_1.stl
Micro_SD_Ball_Number_2.stl
Micro_SD_Ball_Number_3.stl
Ball_Stand.stl

Made by my own, and feel free to modify or do a "look-a-like"!

title: GEEETech i3B/C/X (PRINTED version): Extruder End
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Hi,
Also if now GEEETech proposes the Acrylic Prusa I3 pro series, B for single extruder and C for dual extruder, with metallic idler, I’ve see lot of people that still download my old customization for Printed idler, so I’ve think good to “port” the new version of my customization also on old, printed idler!
Here the Extruder End component of my new customization, you can see from attached picture the all electric contacts are now decoupled on top of this component, so you can easy install it and after install extruder!
The decoupler is designed to support:

2 Complete Extruder, with for each power for Hot End, Cable for Motor and Thermocople
3 Fan, one “always on” and two that connected to the two PWM fans if your board have it, or if you have also the Reprap Ramps1.4 RRD Fan Extender on top of classic RAMPS 1.4
1 three wire AutoBed sensor.
2 LED
You can see in Schema all component you need, and all the cables are 160cm length to avoid any complexity during installation

In the schema images you can see how all this cables are connected.

PS: I’ve also add the STL for carriage with some small enhancement compared to original GEEETech ones, for example the x belt fixing method copied from the metal carriage, really more easy to put in place, and the holes to enable the unmounts of “just motor” of dual MK8 with black feeder, un mounting just the motor enable to keep Hot end alignment in case of maintenance!

As usual in all my design I’ve splitted all in order to have an easy print of each part, and also an easy mounting after print!

PLEASE PAY ATTENTION: the decouple is NOT SO EASY to create!
You must be good with a soldering iron!!!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

author: aguia58

description.text:
This is my new compact high flow cooler design for the MK8 extruder.
After trying several different designs, i settled with the Cobra cooler (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1090433) as it provided the best airflow, but it never fitted my printer so i had it held in place by a 1mm aluminium wire harness... i used it for several months, but it was time to design my own that actually fits and doesn't block the view.

I used a physical simulation to create the smooth flowing shape of the "tentacles"; based on the first few tests it provides excellent cooling.
The two C-shaped clips snap nicely on the extruder motor, and the centrifugal fan screws directly onto them using two standard 3mm screws. The actual cooler nozzle snaps on the fan without the need for anything else (a modified version of the Spriya cooler's head http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2133328).

Enjoy!
You might get a few loose strands at the overhangs at the ends when printing; just cut them off, they are just visual imperfections, don't affect the flow.

comments.text:
Yeah it's a bit chicken and egg, right? :)
I actually tried several different ducts before making this one so i already had some cooling to start with. This one is just better and I designed it to print all right even with no support (3D printing is slow enough as it is, why spend time printing throw away stuff?). But, anyway, actually as you can see on the picture, i printed a second one using the first one; so even if you have to print your first one without cooling, just lower the speed, should come out a-okay (mine had a few missing little bits near the end where it curves back in but that makes little difference in the airflow), and if you're not entirely happy you can use it to print a second, better one :)

description.text: This is a 0.2mm spacer for use with old-style safety razors.  If you like the elegance of a safety razor, but find that it is not quite giving you a close enough shave, a spacer may be the answer.  In short, a spacer creates a very small gap between the base of the razor and the blade, which results in a more aggressive shave.  I have printed mine in red as if to say "DANGER....I HAVE DEIGNED TO MAKE THIS SAFETY RAZOR DECIDEDLY LESS SAFE!"  If you print this and use the spacer, please read and follow the instructions, and most of all, take care while shaving as your safety razor is ready to provide an aggressive close shave, which coincidently increases the chances of nicks and cuts.  Printed and used correctly, this object allows those of us with coarse hair to use a safety razor for shaving.  The first picture is the printed spacer next to a razor blade.  You can see the holes match up, as does the length.  But the spacer is about 4mm less in width than the blade.  The second picture shows the assembly of the razor with the spacer.  The order goes; razor top, then razor blade, then spacer, then razor bottom (base).  The third picture is a close up of the assembled unit and you can see the gap between the blade and the base that the spacer creates.  LEGAL NOTE: I hereby absolve myself of any and all blood spilled while employing this 3D print in your shaving regimen.  Be careful and happy shaving!!!

This was printed in ABS at the highest quality, although I am certain PLA would work fine.  High quality is necessary as the object is incredibly thin.  Make certain your packing density (some systems call this setting flow) is set correctly for your printing medium.  A chunky print with even small imperfections may create an unsafe and unusable spacer.  After printing, take a file or sandpaper and make certain that the print is smooth and even on both sides.  I used Cura to slice this.  Other programs might have problems as this is essentially only two Z layers thick.  Please message me if you need me to publish the gcode.  Other tips for printing include slowing down your printer and printing at a slightly elevated temperature.  I slowed my printer down to 40mm/sec and increased the printing temperature for ABS to 255C.  My layer height is 0.1mm.  If you have had luck printing at smaller layer heights, I would suggest giving the finer layers a try.  Most of the other settings like wall/top/bottom thickness and fill density are moot as this is a print with only two Z layers.

author: Greenlucas

description.text:
This is a drain screen for a bathtub/shower to catch hair and other detritus while allowing for proper drainage of the water.
Measures approx. 40mm in diameter and should fit snug or slightly loose in a standard drain when inserted. Pull it out by the center stem to clean it and reuse it until it deteriorates.

Print it at whatever layer height you please (I used 0.2mm) and slower is better. Should only take 30 minutes or so to print. Print as close to 100% infill as you feel comfortable. This ensures a good solid connection between the center stem and the screen.
Place a drop of super glue on the underside of the screen at the center stem spot if you have troubles with the print strength at this location.

title: Holder for Kobo Aura One eBook-Reader

description.text:
The new eBook-Reader Kobo Aura One has an incredible wide screen but because of it's therefore wide case it is nearly impossible for people with normal hands to hold this reader with only one hand without getting cramps.
This holder let you convenient hold the reader with one hand.
I attached two different files for the holder depending if you want to hold the reader with your left or right hand. They are only mirrored.
Print one holder and two clips.

Printer:

FlashForge Dreamer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.20mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Support is only needed as a small wall underneath the hooks holding the reader (see attached picture). Don't generate supports into the slots holding the clips. A well calibrated printer can bridge the first closing layer over the slots and within the clips without problems.
Print with 100% infill for better stability.

If your printer is well calibrated there is no sanding, filing or glue necessary to attach the clips to the holder. They will fit tight to the holders slots. You can use some careful hits to drive the clip into the slot.
You need a piece of hook-and-loop tape or adjustable slipknot-band to fix the holder on your hand. Pull it not too tight. It must only prevent the tipping of the reader.

description.text:
This is a simple mount to hold an android phone on the z brace of an I3 (Wanhao I3, Monoprice Maker Select, etc) printer.

This snaps onto the threaded rod of your z brace and allows you to use an old Android phone as an IP webcam for monitoring your printer. The tabs on the top and the bottom allow a rubber band to be used to hold the phone steady. You can run a couple of nuts on the top and bottom of this on your threaded rod to hold it steady.

comments.text: Printed well for me and fit on my 1/4-20 z brace rod. My intention was to use this for time lapse photography however I recommend you DO NOT use this for that application as this style printer has a moving bed and makes for bad time lapses. For good videos you either need some software to control when to collect the image or you need to mount your camera onto the bed.
